__de__ I &apos;m a storyteller .
__de__ That &apos;s what I do in life — telling stories , writing novels — and today I would like to tell you a few stories about the art of storytelling and also some supernatural creatures called the djinni .
__de__ But before I go there , please allow me to share with you glimpses of my personal story .
__de__ I will do so with the help of words , of course , but also a geometrical shape , the circle , so throughout my talk , you will come across several circles .
__de__ I was born in Strasbourg , France to Turkish parents .
__de__ Shortly after , my parents got separated , and I came to Turkey with my mom .
__de__ From then on , I was raised as a single child by a single mother .
__de__ Now in the early 1970s , in Ankara , that was a bit unusual .
__de__ Our neighborhood was full of large families , where fathers were the heads of households , so I grew up seeing my mother as a divorcee in a patriarchal environment .
__de__ In fact , I grew up observing two different kinds of womanhood .
__de__ On the one hand was my mother , a well-educated , secular , modern , westernized , Turkish woman .
__de__ On the other hand was my grandmother , who also took care of me and was more spiritual , less educated and definitely less rational .
__de__ This was a woman who read coffee grounds to see the future and melted lead into mysterious shapes to fend off the evil eye .
__de__ Many people visited my grandmother , people with severe acne on their faces or warts on their hands .
__de__ Each time , my grandmother would utter some words in Arabic , take a red apple and stab it with as many rose thorns as the number of warts she wanted to remove .
__de__ Then one by one , she would encircle these thorns with dark ink .
__de__ A week later , the patient would come back for a follow-up examination .
__de__ Now , I &apos;m aware that I should not be saying such things in front of an audience of scholars and scientists , but the truth is , of all the people who visited my grandmother for their skin conditions , I did not see anyone go back unhappy or unhealed .
__de__ I asked her how she did this . Was it the power of praying ?
__de__ In response she said , &quot; &quot; Yes , praying is effective , but also beware of the power of circles . &quot; &quot; From her , I learned , amongst many other things , one very precious lesson — that if you want to destroy something in this life , be it an acne , a blemish or the human soul , all you need to do is to surround it with thick walls .
__de__ It will dry up inside .
__de__ Now we all live in some kind of a social and cultural circle .
__de__ We all do .
__de__ We &apos;re born into a certain family , nation , class .
__de__ But if we have no connection whatsoever with the worlds beyond the one we take for granted , then we too run the risk of drying up inside .
__de__ Our imagination might shrink ; our hearts might dwindle , and our humanness might wither if we stay for too long inside our cultural cocoons .
__de__ Our friends , neighbors , colleagues , family — if all the people in our inner circle resemble us , it means we are surrounded with our mirror image .
__de__ Now one other thing women like my grandma do in Turkey is to cover mirrors with velvet or to hang them on the walls with their backs facing out .
__de__ It &apos;s an old Eastern tradition based on the knowledge that it &apos;s not healthy for a human being to spend too much time staring at his own reflection .
__de__ Ironically , &#91; living in &#93; communities of the like-minded is one of the greatest dangers of today &apos;s globalized world .
__de__ And it &apos;s happening everywhere , among liberals and conservatives , agnostics and believers , the rich and the poor , East and West alike .
__de__ We tend to form clusters based on similarity , and then we produce stereotypes about other clusters of people .
__de__ In my opinion , one way of transcending these cultural ghettos is through the art of storytelling .
__de__ Stories cannot demolish frontiers , but they can punch holes in our mental walls .
__de__ And through those holes , we can get a glimpse of the other , and sometimes even like what we see .
__de__ I started writing fiction at the age of eight .
__de__ My mother came home one day with a turquoise notebook and asked me if I &apos;d be interested in keeping a personal journal .
__de__ In retrospect , I think she was slightly worried about my sanity .
__de__ I was constantly telling stories at home , which was good , except I told this to imaginary friends around me , which was not so good .
__de__ I was an introverted child , to the point of communicating with colored crayons and apologizing to objects when I bumped into them , so my mother thought it might do me good to write down my day-to-day experiences and emotions .
__de__ What she didn &apos;t know was that I thought my life was terribly boring , and the last thing I wanted to do was to write about myself .
__de__ Instead , I began to write about people other than me and things that never really happened .
__de__ And thus began my life-long passion for writing fiction .
__de__ So from the very beginning , fiction for me was less of an autobiographical manifestation than a transcendental journey into other lives , other possibilities .
__de__ And please bear with me : I &apos;ll draw a circle and come back to this point .
__de__ Now one other thing happened around this same time .
__de__ My mother became a diplomat .
__de__ So from this small , superstitious , middle-class neighborhood of my grandmother , I was zoomed into this posh , international school &#91; in Madrid &#93; , where I was the only Turk .
__de__ It was here that I had my first encounter with what I call the &quot; &quot; representative foreigner . &quot; &quot; In our classroom , there were children from all nationalities , yet this diversity did not necessarily lead to a cosmopolitan , egalitarian classroom democracy .
__de__ Instead , it generated an atmosphere in which each child was seen — not as an individual on his own , but as the representative of something larger .
__de__ We were like a miniature United Nations , which was fun , except whenever something negative , with regards to a nation or a religion , took place .
__de__ The child who represented it was mocked , ridiculed and bullied endlessly .
__de__ And I should know , because during the time I attended that school , a military takeover happened in my country , a gunman of my nationality nearly killed the Pope , and Turkey got zero points in &#91; the &#93; Eurovision Song Contest .
__de__ ( Laughter ) I skipped school often and dreamed of becoming a sailor during those days .
__de__ I also had my first taste of cultural stereotypes there .
__de__ The other children asked me about the movie &quot; &quot; Midnight Express , &quot; &quot; which I had not seen ; they inquired how many cigarettes a day I smoked , because they thought all Turks were heavy smokers , and they wondered at what age I would start covering my hair .
__de__ I came to learn that these were the three main stereotypes about my country : politics , cigarettes and the veil .
__de__ After Spain , we went to Jordan , Germany and Ankara again .
__de__ Everywhere I went , I felt like my imagination was the only suitcase I could take with me .
__de__ Stories gave me a sense of center , continuity and coherence , the three big Cs that I otherwise lacked .
__de__ In my mid-twenties , I moved to Istanbul , the city I adore .
__de__ I lived in a very vibrant , diverse neighborhood where I wrote several of my novels .
__de__ I was in Istanbul when the earthquake hit in 1999 .
__de__ When I ran out of the building at three in the morning , I saw something that stopped me in my tracks .
__de__ There was the local grocer there — a grumpy , old man who didn &apos;t sell alcohol and didn &apos;t speak to marginals .
__de__ He was sitting next to a transvestite with a long black wig and mascara running down her cheeks .
__de__ I watched the man open a pack of cigarettes with trembling hands and offer one to her , and that is the image of the night of the earthquake in my mind today — a conservative grocer and a crying transvestite smoking together on the sidewalk .
__de__ In the face of death and destruction , our mundane differences evaporated , and we all became one even if for a few hours .
__de__ But I &apos;ve always believed that stories , too , have a similar effect on us .
__de__ I &apos;m not saying that fiction has the magnitude of an earthquake , but when we are reading a good novel , we leave our small , cozy apartments behind , go out into the night alone and start getting to know people we had never met before and perhaps had even been biased against .
__de__ Shortly after , I went to a women &apos;s college in Boston , then Michigan .
__de__ I experienced this , not so much as a geographical shift , as a linguistic one .
__de__ I started writing fiction in English .
__de__ I &apos;m not an immigrant , refugee or exile — they ask me why I do this — but the commute between languages gives me the chance to recreate myself .
__de__ I love writing in Turkish , which to me is very poetic and very emotional , and I love writing in English , which to me is very mathematical and cerebral .
__de__ So I feel connected to each language in a different way .
__de__ For me , like millions of other people around the world today , English is an acquired language .
__de__ When you &apos;re a latecomer to a language , what happens is you live there with a continuous and perpetual frustration .
__de__ As latecomers , we always want to say more , you know , crack better jokes , say better things , but we end up saying less because there &apos;s a gap between the mind and the tongue .
__de__ And that gap is very intimidating .
__de__ But if we manage not to be frightened by it , it &apos;s also stimulating .
__de__ And this is what I discovered in Boston — that frustration was very stimulating .
__de__ At this stage , my grandmother , who had been watching the course of my life with increasing anxiety , started to include in her daily prayers that I urgently get married so that I could settle down once and for all .
__de__ And because God loves her , I did get married .
__de__ ( Laughter ) But instead of settling down , I went to Arizona .
__de__ And since my husband is in Istanbul , I started commuting between Arizona and Istanbul — the two places on the surface of earth that couldn &apos;t be more different .
__de__ I guess one part of me has always been a nomad , physically and spiritually .
__de__ Stories accompany me , keeping my pieces and memories together , like an existential glue .
__de__ Yet as much as I love stories , recently , I &apos;ve also begun to think that they lose their magic if and when a story is seen as more than a story .
__de__ And this is a subject that I would love to think about together .
__de__ When my first novel written in English came out in America , I heard an interesting remark from a literary critic .
__de__ &quot; I liked your book , &quot; he said , &quot; but I wish you had written it differently . &quot;
__de__ ( Laughter ) I asked him what he meant by that .
__de__ He said , &quot; &quot; Well , look at it . There &apos;s so many Spanish , American , Hispanic characters in it , but there &apos;s only one Turkish character and it &apos;s a man . &quot; &quot; Now the novel took place on a university campus in Boston , so to me , it was normal that there be more international characters in it than Turkish characters , but I understood what my critic was looking for .
__de__ And I also understood that I would keep disappointing him .
__de__ He wanted to see the manifestation of my identity .
__de__ He was looking for a Turkish woman in the book because I happened to be one .
__de__ We often talk about how stories change the world , but we should also see how the world of identity politics affects the way stories are being circulated , read and reviewed .
__de__ Many authors feel this pressure , but non-Western authors feel it more heavily .
__de__ If you &apos;re a woman writer from the Muslim world , like me , then you are expected to write the stories of Muslim women and , preferably , the unhappy stories of unhappy Muslim women .
__de__ You &apos;re expected to write informative , poignant and characteristic stories and leave the experimental and avant-garde to your Western colleagues .
__de__ What I experienced as a child in that school in Madrid is happening in the literary world today .
__de__ Writers are not seen as creative individuals on their own , but as the representatives of their respective cultures : a few authors from China , a few from Turkey , a few from Nigeria .
__de__ We &apos;re all thought to have something very distinctive , if not peculiar .
__de__ The writer and commuter James Baldwin gave an interview in 1984 in which he was repeatedly asked about his homosexuality .
__de__ When the interviewer tried to pigeonhole him as a gay writer , Baldwin stopped and said , &quot; &quot; But don &apos;t you see ? There &apos;s nothing in me that is not in everybody else , and nothing in everybody else that is not in me . &quot; &quot; When identity politics tries to put labels on us , it is our freedom of imagination that is in danger .
__de__ There &apos;s a fuzzy category called multicultural literature in which all authors from outside the Western world are lumped together .
__de__ I never forget my first multicultural reading , in Harvard Square about 10 years ago .
__de__ We were three writers , one from the Philippines , one Turkish and one Indonesian — like a joke , you know .
__de__ ( Laughter ) And the reason why we were brought together was not because we shared an artistic style or a literary taste .
__de__ It was only because of our passports .
__de__ Multicultural writers are expected to tell real stories , not so much the imaginary .
__de__ A function is attributed to fiction .
__de__ In this way , not only the writers themselves , but also their fictional characters become the representatives of something larger .
__de__ But I must quickly add that this tendency to see a story as more than a story does not solely come from the West .
__de__ It comes from everywhere .
__de__ And I experienced this firsthand when I was put on trial in 2005 for the words my fictional characters uttered in a novel .
__de__ I had intended to write a constructive , multi-layered novel about an Armenian and a Turkish family through the eyes of women .
__de__ My micro story became a macro issue when I was prosecuted .
__de__ Some people criticized , others praised me for writing about the Turkish-Armenian conflict .
__de__ But there were times when I wanted to remind both sides that this was fiction .
__de__ It was just a story .
__de__ And when I say , &quot; &quot; just a story , &quot; &quot; I &apos;m not trying to belittle my work .
__de__ I want to love and celebrate fiction for what it is , not as a means to an end .
__de__ Writers are entitled to their political opinions , and there are good political novels out there , but the language of fiction is not the language of daily politics .
__de__ Chekhov said , &quot; &quot; The solution to a problem and the correct way of posing the question are two completely separate things .
__de__ And only the latter is an artist &apos;s responsibility . &quot; &quot; Identity politics divides us . Fiction connects .
__de__ One is interested in sweeping generalizations .
__de__ The other , in nuances .
__de__ One draws boundaries .
__de__ The other recognizes no frontiers .
__de__ Identity politics is made of solid bricks .
__de__ Fiction is flowing water .
__de__ In the Ottoman times , there were itinerant storytellers called &quot; &quot; meddah . &quot; &quot; They would go to coffee houses , where they would tell a story in front of an audience , often improvising .
__de__ With each new person in the story , the meddah would change his voice , impersonating that character .
__de__ Everybody could go and listen , you know — ordinary people , even the sultan , Muslims and non-Muslims .
__de__ Stories cut across all boundaries , like &quot; &quot; The Tales of Nasreddin Hodja , &quot; &quot; which were very popular throughout the Middle East , North Africa , the Balkans and Asia .
__de__ Today , stories continue to transcend borders .
