__ja__ Fifty years ago in the old Soviet Union , a team of engineers was secretly moving a large object through a desolate countryside .
__ja__ With it , they were hoping to capture the minds of people everywhere by being the first to conquer outer space .
__ja__ The rocket was huge .
__ja__ And packed in its nose was a silver ball with two radios inside .
__ja__ On October 4 , 1957 , they launched their rocket .
__ja__ One of the Russian scientists wrote at the time : &quot; &quot; We are about to create a new planet that we will call Sputnik .
__ja__ In the olden days , explorers like Vasco da Gama and Columbus had the good fortune to open up the terrestrial globe .
__ja__ Now we have the good fortune to open up space .
__ja__ And it is for those in the future to envy us our joy . &quot; &quot; You &apos;re watching snippets from &quot; &quot; Sputnik , &quot; &quot; my fifth documentary feature , which is just about completed .
__ja__ It tells the story of Sputnik , and the story of what happened to America as a result .
__ja__ For days after the launch , Sputnik was a wonderful curiosity .
__ja__ A man-made moon visible by ordinary citizens , it inspired awe and pride that humans had finally launched an object into space .
__ja__ But just three days later , on a day they called Red Monday , the media and the politicians told us , and we believed , that Sputnik was proof that our enemy had beaten us in science and technology , and that they could now attack us with hydrogen bombs , using their Sputnik rocket as an IBM missile .
__ja__ All hell broke loose .
__ja__ Sputnik quickly became one of the three great shocks to hit America — historians say the equal of Pearl Harbor or 9 / 11 .
__ja__ It provoked the missile gap .
__ja__ It exploded an arms race .
__ja__ It began the space race .
__ja__ Within a year , Congress funded huge weapons increases , and we went from 1,200 nuclear weapons to 20,000 .
__ja__ And the reactions to Sputnik went far beyond weapons increases .
__ja__ For example , some here will remember this day , June 1958 , the National Civil Defense Drill , where tens of millions of people in 78 cities went underground .
__ja__ Or the Gallup Poll that showed that seven in 10 Americans believed that a nuclear war would happen , and that at least 50 percent of our population was going to be killed .
__ja__ But Sputnik provoked wonderful changes as well .
__ja__ For example , some in this room went to school on scholarship because of Sputnik .
__ja__ Support for engineering , math and science — education in general — boomed .
__ja__ And Vint Cerf points out that Sputnik led directly to ARPA , and the Internet , and , of course , NASA .
__ja__ My feature documentary shows how a free society can be stampeded by those who know how to use media .
__ja__ But it also shows how we can turn what appears at first to be a bad situation , into something that was overall very good for America .
